==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Soul
<hw>Soul</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>so⟦ucir⟧ler</ets> to
satiate. See <er>Soil</er> to feed.]</ety> <def>To afford suitable
sustenance.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Warner.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Soul</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Soul
<hw>Soul</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>soule</ets>,
<ets>saule</ets>, AS. <ets>s⟦amac⟧wel</ets>, <ets>s⟦amac⟧wl</ets>; akin
to OFries. <ets>s<?/le</ets>, OS. <ets>s<?/ola</ets>, D.
<ets>ziel</ets>, G. <ets>seele</ets>, OHG. <ets>s<?/la</ets>,
<ets>s<?/ula</ets>, Icel. <ets>s⟦amac⟧la</ets>, Sw. <ets>sj⟦aum⟧l</ets>,
Dan. <ets>siael</ets>, Goth. <ets>saiwala</ets>; of uncertain origin,
perhaps akin to L. <ets>saeculum</ets> a lifetime, age (cf.
<er>Secular</er>.)]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The spiritual, rational, and
immortal part in man; that part of man which enables him to think, and
which renders him a subject of moral government; -- sometimes, in
distinction from the higher nature, or spirit, of man, the so-called
animal soul, that is, the seat of life, the sensitive affections and
phantasy, exclusive of the voluntary and rational powers; -- sometimes,
in distinction from the mind, the moral and emotional part of man's
nature, the seat of feeling, in distinction from intellect; --
sometimes, the intellect only; the understanding; the seat of knowledge,
as distinguished from <xex>feeling</xex>. In a more general sense,
⟦ldquo⟧an animating, separable, surviving entity, the vehicle of
individual personal existence.⟦rdquo⟧</def> <rj><au>Tylor.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The eyes of our <qex>souls</qex> only then begin to see, when our
bodily eyes are closing.</q> <rj><qau>Law.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The seat of real life or vitality; the source of
action; the animating or essential part.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The hidden
<xex>soul</xex> of harmony.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thou sun, of this great world both eye and <qex>soul</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The leader; the inspirer; the moving spirit; the
heart; <as>as, the <ex>soul</ex> of an enterprise; an able general is
the <ex>soul</ex> of his army</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He is the very <qex>soul</qex> of bounty!</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Energy; courage; spirit; fervor; affection, or any
other noble manifestation of the heart or moral nature; inherent power
or goodness.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That he wants algebra he must confess;⟦br⟧
But not a <qex>soul</qex> to give our arms success.</q>
<rj><qau>Young.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>A human being; a person; -- a familiar appellation,
usually with a qualifying epithet; <as>as, poor
<ex>soul</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>As cold waters to a thirsty <qex>soul</qex>, so is good news from
a far country.</q> <rj><qau>Prov. xxv. 25.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>God forbid so many simple <qex>souls</qex>⟦br⟧
Should perish by the sword!</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Now mistress Gilpin (careful <qex>soul</qex>).</q>
<rj><qau>Cowper.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>A pure or disembodied spirit.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That to his only Son . . . every <qex>soul</qex> in heaven⟦br⟧
Shall bend the knee.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>A perceived shared community and awareness among
African-Americans.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>Soul music.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Soul</xex> is used in the formation of numerous
compounds, most of which are of obvious signification; as,
<xex>soul</xex>-betraying, <xex>soul</xex>-consuming,
<xex>soul</xex>-destroying, <xex>soul</xex>-distracting,
<xex>soul</xex>-enfeebling, <xex>soul</xex>-exalting,
<xex>soul</xex>-felt, <xex>soul</xex>-harrowing,
<xex>soul</xex>-piercing, <xex>soul</xex>-quickening,
<xex>soul</xex>-reviving, <xex>soul</xex>-stirring,
<xex>soul</xex>-subduing, <xex>soul</xex>-withering, etc.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Spirit; life; courage; fire; ardor.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Cure of souls</b></col>. <cd>See <er>Cure</er>,
<pos>n.</pos>, 2.</cd> -- <col><b>Soul bell</b></col>, <cd>the passing
bell.</cd> <au>Bp. Hall.</au> -- <col><b>Soul foot</b></col>. <cd>See
<cref>Soul scot</cref>, below.</cd> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> -- <col><b>Soul
scot</b></col> <it>or</it> <col><b>Soul shot</b></col>.
<ety>[<ets>Soul</ets> + <ets>scot</ets>, or <ets>shot</ets>; cf. AS.
<ets>s⟦amac⟧welsceat</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(O. Eccl. Law)</fld> <cd>A
funeral duty paid in former times for a requiem for the soul.</cd>
<au>Ayliffe.</au> </cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Soul</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Soul
<hw>Soul</hw> <pr>(s⟦omac⟧l)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To indue with a
soul; to furnish with a soul or mind.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>soul</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: soul
<hw>soul</hw> <pr>(s⟦omac⟧l)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>By or for
African-Americans, or characteristic of their culture; <as>as,
<ex>soul</ex> music; <ex>soul</ex> newspapers; <ex>soul</ex>
food</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Souled</ent>⟦br⟧
